Title: Stone House Musical B&B
Content: This Fall Pilgrimage Tour House furnished with period antiques includes live classical piano music with wine, hot breakfast served on antique Limoges china, an antebellum billiard hall and Gallery of Antique Maps and Prints, all in one convenient location! Winner of TripAdvisor 2012 & 2013 Travelers' Choice Awards for the Top 25 B&B's in USA. Please visit our website for more details.

Title: Natchez Grand Hotel
Content:
Located across the street from the Natchez Convention Center, the Natchez Grand Hotel located in the heart of downtown Natchez. Opened in the Spring of 2008, the Grand was a welcomed addition to downtown lodging, offering 119 additional rooms to entice meeting and convention planners to Natchez.
19 of the rooms are suites and all are quite comfortable and elegantly appointed. Be sure to ask for a river view room when you call to book your stay.

Title: Biscuits & Blues
Content: Come on in to Biscuits and Blues for a full evening of great food, great drink, and lots of friendly folks. There is a nightly happy hour, and they offer a nice variety of imported beers at this Natchez nightlife favorite. Savor award winning cuisine and the best California wines, micro-brews, and specialty cocktails.

Title: Devereaux Shields House
Content: Plan your next getaway to our elegant Natchez bed and breakfast. Set in the heart of the historic district of Natchez, Mississippi, Devereaux Shields House offers two separate properties, one of which is pet friendly. We offer an ideal location that is only a few block from downtown restaurants, shopping and attractions. Experience true Southern Hospitality with a delicious full breakfast each morning, beautiful gardens and thoughtfully appointed guestrooms, including 2-room suites. Join us for a romantic getaway in Mississippi you will never forget! Give the gift of a getaway this season with a Devereaux Shields House gift certificate!

Title: The Guest House
Content: Located in the heart of historic downtown Natchez, the Guest House features 16 beautiful rooms. Appointed with antiques and antique reproductions, each of our guest rooms also offers modern conveniences such as a cable television, in-room telephone, an alarm clock, and wireless Internet access. There are two large verandas which front the building where guests are welcome to sip an evening cocktail while rocking their cares away in the breeze. When you walk out the door, you are just steps away from antiques row and only a block from most shopping and dining. Your stay at the Guest House will truly be a memorable one.

Title: Days Inn
Content: The Days Inn of Natchez is an upscale version of the national chain and is located on the northbound lane of Hwy. 61 South, just minutes from downtown. There are 123 rooms available and a number of restaurants, both local fare and national chains nearby. This unique property features beautifully finished deluxe rooms visited by celebrities such as actors John Wayne and William Holden, and Director John Ford. There is a complimentary dinner served Monday thru Thursday (until it's all gone), and there is a complimentary breakfast buffet complete with waffles to start your day.

Title: Hampton Inn & Suites
Content: Business travelers and vacationers alike will want a hotel that offers modern amenities with incredible service. That's just what you'll find at the Hampton Inn & Suites Natchez, MS hotel. Conveniently located on the banks of the Mississippi River, it offers the ideal place to relax and enjoy the awe-inspiring view. Whatever your pleasure-from antebellum home tours to picnics on the bluff-you'll find it all near this comfortable Natchez hotel.

Title: Monmouth Historic Inn
Content: Monmouth is listed as a National Historic Landmark, resting on 26 beautifully landscaped acres, and no matter which facility your guest room is in, all are comfortable and luxuriously furnished. Daily 10 AM and 2 PM tour of the historic property may be purchased at the home.

Title: Wilkins Town House
Content: The 1835 Wilkins Town House has two exquisitely furnished suites from which to choose. Each suite can sleep up to four people with a queen size bed and queen size sofa-bed in each parlor. You'll feel like you've stepped back in time with the 12 foot ceilings in the suites and main living area. The Wilkins Town House bed and breakfast is located in the downtown area close to dining and shopping.

Listing Amenity: Breakfast Included|Credit Cards Accepted|Downtown Walking Distance|Historic Property|Internet Access|Private Bath
Title: Pleasant Hill
Content: This cozy bed and breakfast is located just two blocks from the business and shopping district of downtown Natchez. Pleasant Hill is an excellent example of a well designed and executed city residence of the 1830's. All guests will be provided with a private bath, a tour of the home, complimentary refreshments in the tropical sunroom and a casual, but full, breakfast to start your morning.

Title: Aunt Clara's Cottage
Content:
Aunt Clara's Cottage bed and breakfast provides four spacious rooms in a charming 1870's
Victorian with heart pine floors, large veranda and ample sitting areas. There is also a reading room. 
The Cottage rooms are popular for budget conscious guests, and family and group getaways desiring privacy.

Listing Amenity: Breakfast Included|Historic Property|Internet Access|Outdoor Pool|Private Bath
Title: Burn, The
Content: This classic 1834 Greek Revival historic home offers 5 comfortable rooms for overnight accommodations. The house is located close to downtown and has a pool for guest use when weather permits. Visit their website for more details on rooms and rates.

Listing Amenity: Breakfast Included|Credit Cards Accepted|Historic Property|Internet Access|Pets Allowed (under 25lbs)|Private Bath
Title: Glenfield
Content: Built in two distinct architectural periods (1787 Spanish and 1840 English Gothic), Glenfield Plantation is a one level Bed and Breakfast, historically preserved, and has been in the same family for seven generations. Glenfield Plantation still rest on the original 150 acre Spanish Land Grant, and witnessed one of the few Civil War skirmishes in the Natchez area. Listed on the National Register of Historic Places,Glenfield Plantation offers visitors and guest a tranquil setting, private accommodations, and modern amenities. Located 1 mile from downtown Natchez, MS, Glenfield welcomes children of all ages, and is pet friendly.

Title: Linden
Content: When you come to stay at Linden, you will reside within the walls of the home; there are no dependencies or out-buildings at Linden. You will be served breakfast in the formal dining room, as favored guests should. After breakfast you will be treated to a tour of Linden, usually given by the owner, Mrs. Jeanette Feltus. Please visit our website for more details.

Listing Amenity: Breakfast Included|Credit Cards Accepted|Downtown Walking Distance|Historic Property|Internet Access|Laundry Facility Available|Pets Allowed (under 25lbs)|River Views
Title: Mark Twain Guesthouse
Content: This unique property is located above the truly historic Under-the-Hill Saloon, once the hangout for renegades, thieves, prostitutes and cut-throats. One of the rooms opens up onto a narrow balcony and breathtaking views of the Mississippi River. The guest rooms are simple but comfortably furnished and share a common bathroom. If you're up for some action, the bar downstairs has live entertainment on the weekends, and you'll love being able to just meander downstairs, have a few cocktails and know that you don't have to drive an inch. You can also take the short walk down the street to the Isle of Capri Casino for a little gaming action.

Title: Restaurant 1818 at Monmouth Historic Inn
Content: Enjoy a true Antebellum dining experience inside the Main House at Monmouth Historic Inn, a great place to celebrate the holidays and special occasions - or make new memories, for dining at Monmouth makes every moment memorable. Known for: Exquisite Fine Dining * Impeccable Service * Casual Dining in the Quitman Lounge or Courtyard. *One of 10 Dreamy Dining Destinations,* Yahoo Travel

Title: Bellemont Shake Shop
Content: It may not take you back to the days of car hops and rock-n-roll, but the Bellemont Shake Shop will conjure up memories of drive-ins from days gone by. Some locals would take a strong stance and argue that this Natchez restaurant serves the best burger in town, and maybe so, but you can count on it being one of the best you ever tasted, especially if you've eaten just about all the Mickey D's burgers along your Mississippi travel route you can consume.

Title: Castle Restaurant & Pub, The
Content:
Located in an original 1790's carriage house and stables, The Castle is the perfect setting for a wonderful dining experience. Having received the Wine Spectator, "Award of Excellence" since its opening in December of 2000, The Castle Restaurant has a wine selection compared to no other establishment in our area.

The Castle Pub is a cozy English-style pub with an extensive bar and signature drink menu. Here, guests can order from The Castle Restaurant or select appetizers from the Pub menu. The Pub boasts a large selection of domestic and foreign beers.
"Open 7 days for breakfast 7:30-10am, lunch 11-2pm, and dinner 6-9pm Mon-Thu/6-10pm Fri & Sat."

Title: Carriage House Restaurant
Content:
The Carriage House Restaurant on the grounds of Stanton Hall, specializes in delicious southern food, and is prepared with care by the hands and staff of Chef Bingo Starr of New Orleans. Chef Starr has taken great care to preserve the long standing favorite dishes of local patrons and brought a few new succulent entrees with his signature style to the menu like fried soft-shell crab. The Carriage House is owned and operated by the Pilgrimage Garden Club and is located on the Northwest corner of the grounds of historic Stanton Hall.
Be sure to take your tour of Stanton Hall either just before or after lunch so you can enjoy viewing the house while you dine, through the big bay window that centers this Mississippi restaurant's facade. Reservations are not necessary, and the restaurant is closed on Monday and Tuesday. Lunch on Wednesday is reserved for the Rotary Lunch so be sure you put it on your itinerary for the weekend.

Listing Amenity: Breakfast Included|Credit Cards Accepted|Downtown Walking Distance|Historic Property|Internet Access|Private Bath
Title: 1835 Oak Hill Inn
Content: Our main suite downstairs contains a queen-size half tester bed, full bath with a luxurious shower, a refrigerator stocked with soft drinks and spring water, and its own entrance to the study. Two bedrooms are featured upstairs, one of which contains a beautiful tester double bed and a single bed for extra occupancy.

Title: El Potro Restaurant Grill
Content: El Potro is situated on the outskirts of town, but you won't mind the short drive to indulge in the fare of this locally popular Mexican restaurant. There is strong competition between the several "South of the Border" establishments located in Natchez, and locals will argue as to which is best. Those in favor of El Potro, claim their dishes have the freshest ingredients, and the portions are larger than that of their competitors. Just make sure you bring a big appetite with you when you head to El Potro because you won't walk away hungry.

Title: Fat Mama's Tamales
Content: Fat Mama's Tamales is another local favorite and the atmosphere is as festive as the food. Their signature entree is their great tamales, but feel free to toss in a link of boudin (pronounce boo-dan) or some fire and ice pickles to spice up your Fat Mama's dining experience just a tad more. There is a large interior dining room that's heated and cooled, but if the weather is nice you'll have to fight for a table out on the shaded deck.

Title: Jughead's Fish Fry
Content:
Family traditions are a staple in the Natchez area, and when it comes to food, they bare even more weight. Jughead's does just that. Their current location is relatively new, especially when you consider that the current owner's grandfather closed the original Jughead's about twenty-five years back. The great thing though, is that the family recipes have all been handed down, and they bring back memories to the locals who used to drive over twenty miles to the original restaurant. It was located inside the levee toward the Mississippi River, South of Vidalia, Louisiana, and you knew to go there hungry because you'd be treated to all you could eat.
Fried shrimp, oysters, catfish, and pickles are the popular dishes among locals, but you'll want to ask for extra hush puppies because that's their specialty. Don't try asking for their hush-puppy recipe because the most you'll get out of them is a sly grin.

Title: La Fiesta Grande
Content: La Fiesta Grande was Natchez' first full-service Mexican restaurant, and as it grew in popularity, always seemed to need more space. It landed at it's current location on the by-pass, and just about any time of the day you'll see a packed parking lot. The reason for that is the fantastic food they serve. Enchiladas, Burritos, Quesadillas, Tacos, Nachos, and all your south of the border favorites are available, and they offer burgers and chicken strip meals for those who don't dare brave the spicy entrees. The atmosphere is always lively, and on occasion a mariachi band will wind it's way through the tables.

simpleview_listing_LISTINGKEYWORDS: restaurant, local flavor, food, foodie, good eats, restaurants, magnolia, grill, under the hill, riverview
Title: Magnolia Grill
Content: Overlooking the mighty Mississippi at Natchez Under-the-Hill, Magnolia Grill not only has one of the best views of the river, they offer a menu with a wide array of entrees to satisfy nearly every palate. From succulent steaks and seafood, to one of the best burgers you'll ever have. They serve lunch and dinner, and if you are lucky enough to get a corner table on the sun porch at dinner time, you may be treated to a spectacular sunset while you dine. Reservations aren't necessary, but for the best view of the river you'll want to ask for a table on the porch.

simpleview_listing_LISTINGKEYWORDS: historic, historic site, food, foodie, restaurant, sandwiches
Title: Mammy's Cupboard
Content: Many consider this unique restaurant a national treasure, and you won't find another like it anywhere in the world. As you can see from the photo of the restaurant, it lies beneath the skirt of a forty foot tall mammy. They only serve lunch, but the food is wonderful and goes perfectly with the atmosphere. They offer a daily hot plate special, like chicken & dumplings or beef pot pie, but they are famous for their great sandwiches, each of which is served with a side of homemade vegetable soup and a scoop of potato salad. The best part is their desserts, so save room for a piece of lemon or chocolate pie with meringue piled as high as Mammy's skirt.

Title: Natchez Coffee Company
Content:
The Natchez Coffee Company is more than just a coffee shop. Sure they offer coffee, espresso, and flavored cappuccinos, but they also serve sandwiches, salads, and blue bell ice cream. Wireless Internet is available, so bring your laptop to check your e-mail while you treat yourself to a chai tea or cup of joe.
Natchez Coffee Company is located within walking distance of downtown hotels and a number of Natchez area B & B's, and sits right in the midst of downtown shops. Locals gather there for morning coffee, so stop in early and perhaps they'll fill you in on some Natchez history while you're there.

simpleview_listing_LISTINGKEYWORDS: food, BBQ, barbeque, burger, foodie, restaurant
Title: Malt Shop, The
Content: The Malt Shop is not a typical dining establishment for visitors, but if you asked a local where you can find the best burger in town, bar-b-que beef sandwich, or a catfish plate, they'll be tempted to tell you "the Malt Shop." Anyone who's grown up in Natchez in the last 60 years, has indulged in more than their fare share of Malt Shop food. If you order the burger plate, you'd better be hungry because they put two deluxe burgers in the box with your fries or curly cues. The next size burger on the menu is the Jumbo burger, and if you have a real hearty appetite, see if you can handle their famous 1/2 pound "Big Daddy" burger. You can't dine in, but there is a large picnic table out front, and you'll know a lot of the locals that have eaten there over the years because their names are most likely carved into the table's top. It's what everyone did while they were waiting on their order.

Title: Pearl Street Pasta
Content: Another downtown local favorite, Pearl Street Pasta, named for it's location, serves up a wonderful variety of pasta dishes, as well as a beautiful, delicious filet of beef with a rich wine sauce and sauteed mushrooms. Sure, you'll get your standard Italian dishes like spaghetti and meat sauce, lasagna, and fettuccine Alfredo, but Pearl Street takes their pasta dishes to a little higher level, especially when they add a Cajun kick to them. Be sure to try the Cajun shrimp or crawfish and shrimp pasta dishes. Pearl Street also has some very talented mixologists on staff, so if you want to amble up to the bar for a smooth martini before dining, ask the bartender to whip up one of their house specials. Don't be in a rush to get through your dining experience, not because the service is slow, but just because you'll want to hang out there a while.

Title: Pig Out Inn
Content:
If you're walking around downtown Natchez and smell a wonderful hickory based aroma coming from somewhere, just follow your senses to The Pig Out Inn. Tender ribs, chicken, and pork all smoked on a grill just outside the back door await your tastebuds, and side dishes like black bean and corn salsa, potato salad, and baked beans with mustard seeds are there to compliment whichever dish you choose.
When the weather is just too delightful to dine indoors, grab your lunch to go and follow the alley to the bluff, grab a picnic table and enjoy your meal while viewing the mighty Mississippi River.

Title: Planet Thailand
Content: The Karahsin family moved to the U.S. in the late 1990's and opened Planet Thailand in a small Louisiana town about 40 miles from Natchez, but Natchezians loved it so much they would travel the forty plus miles just to eat sushi. After a few years of driving the distance, several Natchez regulars convinced the family to bring the restaurant to Natchez, promising to frequent the establishment often. Well they did, and we do. Locals can always be found indulging in the succulent spicy dishes the family creates at Planet Thailand, so be sure to add it to your dining itinerary during your stay.

Listing Amenity: Breakfast Included|Credit Cards Accepted|Historic Property|Internet Access|Laundry Facility Available|Outdoor Pool|Pets Allowed (under 25lbs)|Private Bath|River Views
Title: Weymouth Hall
Content: This bed and breakfast experience is one of the best you can have in Natchez. This grand, Greek Revival house rests on the highest peak of the Natchez, revealing breathtaking views of the Mighty Mississippi. Park yourself on the front lawn in an Adirondack chair, grab a good book or just watch the river roll by. The rooms are all comfortably furnished as one travel writer even wrote, "the quiet was so soundless, that I enjoyed a deeper slumber than I knew I needed." This majestic home is located just a couple of minutes from downtown, but once you get there, you may not want to venture out anywhere else.

Title: Deluxe Inn
Content: Deluxe Inn is a reasonably priced hotel and located less than five minutes from downtown. The rooms are comfortable and you'll be well taken care of by their friendly staff.

Title: Excellent Inn & Suites
Content: The Excellent Inn & Suites is located right in town on Hwy 61 S near the Natchez Regional Medical Center. There are a variety of chains restaurants, fast food and grocery stores near by. The Excellent Inn has 70 rooms, free high speed internet access, plus HBO & Cinemax. They also offer a free full breakfast everyday. A refrigerator, microwave, coffee maker & ironing board are available in each room.

Title: Hotel VUE
Content: Rest Where the River Bends. Come perch with us on the bluff of the Mississippi River. At Hotel VUE, you can rest assured you'll receive comfort, amenities, and charm. Hotel VUE's history lends itself to a perfect dose of Southern hospitality while its modern vibe ushers guests into the “new” Natchez. At Hotel VUE, you can enjoy majestic river views, cocktails as strong as our accents, and a piping hot breakfast served with a side of Mississippi warmth.

Title: Rodeway Inn
Content: The Rodeway Inn has 50 rooms, free high speed internet access, plus HBO and Cinemax. They also offer a free deluxe continental breakfast everyday! A refrigerator, microwave and coffee maker are available in each room.

Listing Amenity: Breakfast Included|Business Center|Coffee Maker|Credit Cards Accepted|Hair Dryer|Internet Access|Iron & Board|Microwave|Off Street Parking|Pets Allowed (under 25lbs)|Refrigerator
Title: Red Carpet Inn
Content: The Red Carpet Inn has 89 rooms, all including a refrigerator, microwave, coffee maker and USA Today. They also have a free hot breakfast and high speed internet. Red Carpet Inn is also a pet-friendly hotel.

Title: Sissy's Everything Fancy Catering
Content: Sissy Eidt is one of the finest chefs around Natchez, and can prepare just about any type of delicious food for a variety of occasions. She uses only the freshest ingredients and creates a fabulous display of the end result. From chicken wings to stuffed pastas, Sissy can accommodate any taste for any occasion.

Title: Moreton's Flowerland
Content: Moreton's is often recommended by reception venue operators to brides getting married in Natchez, as it is considered by many locals to the best floral shop in Natchez. Brenda Zerby has over 40 years of experience in floral design and works closely with the couple to determine what flowers best coordinate with their personalities and desired wedding setting. Make an appointment to meet with Brenda and her staff for your special day; it will surely make it more special than you imagined.

Title: Flower Station, The
Content: The Flower Station adds to the nice selection of flower shops available in Natchez, whether you are in need of flowers for your wedding or a place to stop in and send flowers should you be traveling on a holiday. They have a great selection and their arrangement skills are second to none.

Title: "O" So Pretty Flowers and Gifts
Content: "O" So Pretty Flowers and Gifts is conveniently located next door to Randall's formal wear, so you can dual task and order flowers and tuxedos for your special day. Make and appointment to view their portfolio of beautiful arrangements, then head over to Randall's and get your husband-to-be and his groomsmen set up too.

Title: King of Hearts
Content: Make sure your groom's tuxedo is almost as stunning as your wedding gown. Designer labels like Bill Blass, Victor Hugo, Versace', and more are available to make sure your future husband looks so handsome that your heart skips a beat when you see him at the altar.

Title: Laird's Barber & Style Shop
Content: The Laird Family has been styling the heads of many Natchez families for years, so should you choose Laird's to perfect your look on your wedding day, you'll know you're in trusted hands. The salon is located just on the edge of the downtown area, so stop by for a consultation as you plan your destination wedding in Natchez.

simpleview_listing_LISTINGKEYWORDS: wedding, weddings, hair, bridal, bride, salon
Title: Mane Event
Content: The Mane Event has a host of stylist that could probably prepare your entire wedding party in one sitting if necessary. It is located close to some of Natchez best destination wedding locale's, so you won't have to travel far with your final look if you're having your nuptials said nearby. Give them a call for consultation for your most precious day.

Title: Dunleith Historic Inn
Content: Dunleith is one of the South's premier all-inclusive wedding destinations. With 26 guest rooms, complete catering services, florist, professional wedding consultants, a pool, and a full-service, on-site restaurant and pub, we are no ordinary venue.

Listing Amenity: Breakfast Included|Business Center|Credit Cards Accepted|Free Parking Lot Available|Hair Dryer|Historic Property|Internet Access|Iron & Board|Jacuzzi Suites|Laundry Service|Long Term Stay Available|Meeting Space Available|Off Street Parking|Outdoor Dining Available|Private Bath|Restaurant|Wireless Internet in Room
Title: Monmouth Historic Inn
Content: One of the premier wedding venues in Natchez is Monmouth Historic Inn, a Four Diamond Small Inn of the World. The staff is exceptional and will make planning your wedding one of the easiest tasks you'll ever undertake. They cater all of their own events, and keep the rear courtyard covered with a see-through tent, simply because they stay booked for weddings almost year round. If you've always imagined having an old-fashioned, deep-South style wedding, Monmouth is just the place to consider.

Title: Rosalie
Content:
Rosalie is nestled atop the bluff overlooking the Mississippi River to the north. The garden area to the east of the house sets up perfectly for a tented reception area. Most brides choose to make their vows on either the front steps or the veranda, while guests enjoy the ceremony from the front lawn, where chairs are placed on either side of a wide walkway.
Picture yourself in a horse-drawn carriage arriving at the front gate and walking down a unique isle toward your future. Rosalie is located within walking distance of four area hotels, so during pleasant weather your guests can casually stroll from their accommodations should they so choose. Be sure to do a site visit at Rosalie when you begin formulating your Natchez wedding plans.

Title: Longwood
Content: Dr. Haller Nutt, 19th century visionary and builder of historic Longwood, probably dreamt that one day he'd see his daughters marry on the steps of their majestic home. Although that never became a reality for Dr. Nutt and his wife, Julia, isn't to say that it can't become a reality for you. If you're looking for a unique wedding location unlike any other in the world, Longwood is exactly what you're looking for. The house and grounds make for a truly majestic setting, and your wedding will be talked about for generations to come. To make an appointment to see Longwood and discuss pricing, setup details, etc., please contact Longwood at the number above. You'll be glad you did, and your friends will be pea green with envy.

Title: Lower Lodge Antiques
Content: Many of the antiques at Lower Lodge are one-of-a-kind and hail from an array of European artisans. Add a visit to Antiques Row to your itinerary during your stay in Natchez, and be sure that Lower Lodge is on your list as a stop. You'll spend a good hour just browsing and chatting with the owner and staff.

Title: Stone Gallery
Content: Make an appointment with J. Stone to get lost in history with rare, early and antique maps, books and prints, all located inside the J.N. Stone House Musicale B&B. Joseph Stone also provides engraved and lithographed maps, botanicals and wildlife prints, historical documents, 16th, 17th 18th & 19th Century items, as well as George Ohr Pottery, Native American Pottery and Navajo weavings.

Title: Old South Trading Post
Content: Southern hospitality is alive and well at The Old South Trading Post. The South is long known for great foods and fun; we carry one of the largest selections of Mississippi and Louisiana items in the region. Whether you are selecting a gift for a special occasion, holiday, or just a special gift, The Old South Trading Post will help you live the legend of the South!

Title: One-of-a-Kind Gifts
Content: One-of-a-Kind Gifts provides customers with the perfect gifts and accessories that will add a sparkle to any special occasion. Whether you need Vera Bradley, jewelry, stationary or seasonal decor, One-of-a-Kind Gifts has everything you could want and more!

Title: Natchez Mall
Content: Looks can be deceiving and there are a lot more stores at the Natchez Mall than meet the eye at first glance. The two major department stores at the Natchez Mall are Belk and Goody's, and there is a Book Land that has called the Natchez Mall home since it opened. A new section was added to the northeast corner of the Mall parking lot and it houses Soda Pops, a Game Stop and more. Be sure to stop by McKenzie's in the Mall center and pick up a box of caramel corn and an ice cold soda.

Listing Amenity: Breakfast Included|Coffee Maker|Downtown Walking Distance|Historic Property|Number of Rooms|Off Street Parking|Private Bath|Refrigerator
Title: Magnolia Cottage
Content: This charming bed and breakfast is located just minutes from downtown. Your stay includes a full southern breakfast delivered to your room by the hostess or served in the formal dining room. Guest enjoy a large romantic cottage with private entrance with a 4 poster queen size bed with canopy, European bath and spacious walk-in closet, fireplace with sitting area, small quaint dining area with fresh flowers and starched linens, includes a small refrigerator stocked with water and ice tea, coffee pot with tea and coffee supplies. Guests receive pastries and/or homemade pecan pralines upon arrival. Additional packages are available upon request.

Title: Grand Village of the Natchez Indians
Content:
Located just on the outskirts of town at the edge of a residential area is The Grand Village of the Natchez Indians. The Natchez Indians inhabited what is now southwest Mississippi ca. 700-1730 AD, with the culture at its zenith in the mid-1500s. Between 1682 and 1729 the Grand Village was their main ceremonial center, according to historical and archaeological evidence. French explorers, priests and journalists descriptions of the ceremonial mounds and archaeological investigations produced additional evidence that the site was the place that the French called "the Grand Village of the Natchez Indians." 

During the period that the Natchez occupied the Grand Village, the French explored the region and began to make settlements. Relations between the French and the Natchez were cordial at first, but deteriorated as various disagreements and episodes of violence arose in 1716 and again in 1723. In 1729, a pro-English element within the tribe led the Natchez to attack the French colonial plantations and military garrison at Fort Rosalie. The French retaliated in such force that the Natchez were forced to abandon their homeland. 

Put the Grand Village on your tour itinerary and pack a picnic lunch to enjoy on the hallowed grounds of this historic treasure.

Title: Natchez City Cemetery
Content:
It may sound a bit grave to consider a cemetery an attraction, but when it comes to the Natchez City Cemetery, and once you learn the history of some of the characters buried there, you'll quickly understand why. Once you enter the gates, you can either begin a self-guided tour following a brochure and map, or you may be interested in hiring a guide so you'll get all the details of the deceased at this historic cemetery You'll hear stories about a woman called Louise the Unfortunate, and a slave named York, or perhaps visit the family plot of famed riverboat Captain, Thomas P. Leathers.

The Natchez City Cemetery is listed on the National Register of Historic places, established in 1822 when remains were moved to the present location from Memorial Park (located behind St. Mary's Basilica downtown). Tombstone inscriptions embellished by romantic and mysterious tales draw portraits of the dearly departed interned here. Bring a good pair of walking shoes and make the Natchez City Cemetery a good three hour stop on your itinerary. As historic cemeteries go, it's unforgettable.

Title: Natchez Museum of African American History and Culture
Content:
The African American Museum of History and Culture contains exhibits from a number of Natchez related African American historic sites, important citizens and events.
Other exhibits within the museum include: The Rhythm Nightclub fire, where over 200 African American Natchez citizens were either burned or trampled to death, information on the Forks of the Road, which was the second largest slave market in the South and some of the literary works of critically acclaimed author Richard Nathaniel Wright, a Natchez native.
Adding the African American Museum of History and Culture to your trip itinerary, will provide you with a look at another dimension of Natchez history that you won't get anywhere else.

Title: Adams County Circuit Clerks Office
Content: Marriage Licenses may be obtained for a fee of $21.00 for your Mississippi wedding. You will need your Drivers License or picture I.D., and the results from your blood test. The Circuit Clerk's office is open Monday through Friday from 8:00 am until 4:30 pm. Phone 601-446-6326 for any additional questions. The Circuit Clerks office is located in the Adams County Courthouse on State Street in downtown Natchez.

Title: Natchez State Park
Content: Natchez State Park is located at 40 Wickcliff Road on Hwy. 61 North. Its amenities include cabins, boat launching, fishing, hiking/nature trail, picnic area/shelter, playground, RV campground and tent campground with restroom/shower facilities.

Title: Plantation RV Park
Content: Plantation Park is located at 1 Frederick Road on Hwy. 61 South, just minutes from Downtown Natchez. Its amenities include RV camping and tent camping with restroom/shower facilities.

Title: River View RV Park & Resort
Content: Riverview RV Park and Resort is located on the landing at Vidalia, LA, just across the river from Natchez. Its amenities include RV camping, primitive tent camping and tent camping with electric and water hook-ups. Meeting space is also available.

Title: 1st Class Limo Service
Content: Oscar Davis runs a 3 vehicle fleet with Lincoln Continental stretch limos. Oscar takes pride in his fleet so his cars are always clean and dependable. His chauffeur staff is friendly and each driver is bonded. Give Oscar a call to take care of all your Mississippi transportation needs.

Title: Natchez Transit System
Content: A great way to transport your guests and wedding party between their accommodations and your wedding and reception venues is via a City trolley. Fashioned after an electric street car like those you'll find in San Francisco and New Orleans running on cables, the Natchez Trollies is a street vehicle that is not limited to track runs and can go just about anywhere you need them too. Your guests and attendants will have a ball on the trolley and they won't have to worry about parking or moving from place to place, which will give them more time to fully enjoy your cherished event. Call us for more details.

Title: Southern Carriage Tours
Content: Complete the enchantment of your wedding day by departing from your reception in a horse-drawn Visa-V carriage. Take a little while to spend some time cuddled up with your new spouse in the comfort of a picture book carriage as your driver takes you on a quiet ride through the downtown area. This is a popular mode of transportation for many a bride who ties the knot in Natchez.

Title: Natchez Pilgrimage Tours
Content:
Natchez Pilgrimage Tour Company offers step-on guides for buses. They have foreign language guides available as well. These guides can narrate an informative tour of the Historic Natchez District. Reservations in advance are required.


NPT staffs guides for the mansions that stay open year-round outside of the annual Pilgrimage festivals in the Spring and the Fall. They are Stanton Hall, Longwood, and the House on Ellicott Hill.

Title: Southern Carriage Tours
Content: Horse-drawn carriages ranging in size from 6 to 10 passengers depart the corner of Canal and State Streets daily, from 10:00 am until dark, on a first-come basis. These tours last approximately 45 minutes to 1 hour through the historic district and the narration points out buildings and areas of historic significance. Arrangements can be made for weddings, or specialty after-hour tours. Tickets may be purchased at the Visitor Center or from the carriage drivers.

Title: Take A Stroll, Self-Guided Downtown Walking Tour
Content:
An excellent way to become familiar with Natchez is by touring the historic downtown area on foot. Most walking tours begin at the Bluff Park, the grassy promenade that skirts Broadway and overlooks the River. 


Pick up your map and Visitors Guide at the Visitor Center located at 640 South Canal Street. Many of the historic sites located on the map are available to stop in and tour year-round, such as the beautifully restored interior of St. Mary Basilica, the historic fountain in Memorial Park just behind St. Mary's, Magnolia Hall, Stanton Hall, First Presbyterian Church, The House on Ellicotts Hill, and Rosalie Mansion.

Title: Clarmount Baptist Church
Content: Clarmount Baptist Church traces its beginnings to 1857, when the congregation purchased land in Giles Bottom. The historic church moved from the low river lands to its present site a few years afterward. The picturesque frame church sits on a knoll out Cemetery Road. The church has an active congregation and provides services open to the public. Service times are listed on a sign in front of the historic church or by calling the number listed on this page.

Title: First Presbyterian Church
Content: First Presbyterian Church, located at the corner of South Pearl and State Streets, is one of the finest examples of a Federal-style church in Mississippi. Constructed in 1828-1829 on the site of an earlier church, it is home to a congregation organized early in the 19th century. Stratton Chapel, added to the rear of the historic church in about 1900, is named for Joseph B. Stratton, pastor at the church from 1843 - 1893 and emeritus for 10 more years until his death. Stratton Chapel houses "Natchez in Historic Photographs", a collection of astonishing photographs of early Natchez from the Gandy Collection. The exhibit is open to the public daily from 9:00 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. and visitors may tour the historic church through the chapel during those hours.

Title: Holy Family Catholic Church
Content: Holy Family Catholic Church, located on the corner of St. Catherine Street and Orange Avenue, was built about 1894, the first Catholic church for a black congregation in the state of Mississippi. The historic church includes a school for children from preschool age through fourth grade. The Holy Family Catholic Church Gospel Choir performs "Southern Road to Freedom" at First Presbyterian each year during Spring Pilgrimage.

Title: Jefferson Street United Methodist Church
Content: Jefferson Street United Methodist Church is located on the corner of Jefferson Street and North Union Street. It is a handsome building constructed in 1872 on the site of two earlier churches. The congregation, one of the earliest in the state, built its first church in 1807. A large family life center was recently added on the west of the main building. The church is open to visitors from 8:30 a.m. to 4:00 p.m.

Title: Pine Ridge Presbyterian Church
Content: Pine Ridge Presbyterian Church is located approximately 7 miles north of Natchez on Pine Ridge Road, which begins as Martin Luther King, Jr. Street in downtown Natchez. It celebrates its 202nd birthday in 2009. The church is a simple brick structure with beautiful details. Most of it  withstood a tornado in the early 20th century and was rebuilt, and it continues to be home to an active congregation.

Title: Rose Hill Baptist Church
Content: Rose Hill Baptist Church was organized before the Civil War and is the oldest organized black Baptist congregation in Mississippi. The church is located on Madison Street between Rankin and Martin Luther King, Jr. Streets. The present brick church building, constructed in 1908, stands on the site of an earlier frame building that burned in 1907.

Title: St. John's United Methodist Church
Content: St. John's is one of the oldest African-American church buildings in Natchez. Set near the street on Martin Luther King, Jr. at the intersection of High Street, the brick church has served as a place of worship for its congregation since about 1886.

Title: St. Mary Basilica
Content:
St. Mary Basilica is a minor basilica, once the cathedral for the state diocese. The oldest Catholic building still in use in Mississippi, the church received its first blessing in 1843. Today, recently restored, the interior of the church is stunning in its artistry and color. The church, a landmark in the city, is an exquisite example of Gothic Revival architecture. 

It is located at the corner of Main and Union Streets, and sits beside a beautiful city park where visitors may stroll, rest or picnic. St. Mary Basilica is open to the public daily (hours vary according to Holy days), and self-guided tour brochures are available in English, French, and German.

Title: Temple B'nai Israel
Content:
Temple B'nai Israel, located at South Commerce and Washington Streets, is the Jewish house of worship built in 1905 to replace the 1872 structure that stood on the same site. The temple has a congregation of only a few remaining Jewish families. 
In the 19th century, however, many prosperous Jewish merchants lived in Natchez and enhanced the city's social, cultural and business vitality. 
Available to tour by appointment; please call the number listed above.

Title: Trinity Episcopal Church
Content: Trinity Episcopal Church, across Washington Street from Temple B'nai Israel, is the oldest church building in Natchez. The congregation is the second oldest of the denomination in the state. Founded in 1822, the church was completed soon after, built in the Federal style with a gilded dome. A remodeling of the church gave it its present handsome Greek Revival appearance. Visitors may enter the church through the center doors to view the interior between 9:30 a.m. and 4:00 p.m.

Title: Washington Methodist Church
Content: Washington Methodist Church is in the village of Washington, Mississippi, about 8 miles north of Natchez on Hwy. 61. The church is considered the birthplace of Methodism for the state, as it is the first Methodist church organized in the Mississippi Territory. The present church, located across the highway from Historic Jefferson College, was built in 1828 of hand-made sun-dried bricks.

Title: Zion Chapel African Methodist Episcopal Church
Content: Zion Chapel African Methodist Episcopal Church is located at Martin Luther King, Jr. and Jefferson Streets. Built in 1858 as Second Presbyterian Church, it was sold to the AME church in 1866. Hiram R. Revels became the first minister. Revels went on to become the first black man to serve in either house of the U.S. Congress when he filled the unexpired Senate term of Jefferson Davis in 1870. Revels also went on to become the first president of Alcorn A&M College, which is now Alcorn State University, in Lorman Mississippi.

Title: Bandstand on the Natchez Bluff
Content: The Natchez Bluff Gazebo is available for weddings for $150, and on a first come first served basis. For further information or to book the gazebo, call City Hall at 601-445-7500.

Title: Clark Creek Nature Area
Content:
Clark Creek Nature Area is located approximately 36 miles south of Natchez near the little towns of Woodville and Fort Adams, Mississippi. There are over 700 acres of steep loess bluffs, woodlands with 30 foot high waterfalls, winding trails, and rugged terrain. It is one of the states most beautiful, unspoiled nature areas. At the trail head there is a c. 1800s country store, and cabins available to rent. 


Phone 601-888-3998 or 800-467-2757 for additional information.

Title: Beau Pre' Country Club
Content:
Beau Pre' Country Club is nestled along picturesque Second Creek in the premier residential area in Natchez. This Mississippi golf course is an 18-hole championship layout designed by Mike Young, and presents a variety of tees, from 5100 yards to 7000 yards, to challenge golfers of all levels. Beau Pre' ("beautiful meadow") has preserved the natural setting and features a dramatic ninety-foot sheer clay bluff, deep ravines, abundant wildlife, rolling terrain and expansive sand areas. 3 miles south of Natchez off Highway 61 South. For golfing tee times call (601) 442-8181.

Course Profile
Type: SP
Holes: 18
Ydg: 6,442
Rtg: 70.9
Slp: 122
Par: 72

You'll also enjoy Beau Pre' Tennis Courts. For court use and Tee times, call (601) 442-8181.

Title: Duncan Park Golf Course
Content:
Duncan Park Golf Course is the home of the Historical Back Nine at Duncan Park. Established in Cica 1916 on land donated by the Stephen Duncan Family in 1908.
The family also donated his now historic home, Auburn, which rests at the North end of the vast acreage. This elegant 18 hole,6350 yard, par 71 golf course journeys through a garden like, hardwood forest featuring beautiful flowering dogwoods, azaleas, Crepe Myrtle's and towering Long Leaf Pine trees and Live Oaks draped with Spanish Moss.
The two distinctive 9 holes layouts awaits your challenge.
The front nine built in 1993 is a Brain Ault design that features rolling terrain and undulating Dwarf Bermuda greens. The historical back nine, established in circa 1916 is rumored to be designed by famed Scottish designer Seymour Dunn, weaves through our family oriented park. This gentle topography rewards accurate drives and precision short irons. One of our famous visitors, Walter Hagen put on an exhibition here and played a match on the "old Nine" prior to his 1924 US Open victory, Sam Snead played the course when he came thru in 1939.
Duncan Park Golf Course features a driving range, fully equipped Pro Shop and rental clubs for those needing them. 

Duncan Park Golf Course is a Public Facility where tourist are always welcome.
"Come out an play a Piece of History"
601 442 5955
Golf Course Profile
Type: PU
Holes: 18
Yds: 6,355
Rtg: 69.4
Slp: 117
Par: 71

Title: Corner Bar, The
Content: The Corner is a popular hangout for locals and a great place for visitors to get some inside information from them on what to see and do while you're in Natchez. Wednesday night is steak night and the owner's grill delicious rib-eyes that you can either consume there or take back to your hotel or B&B if you like.

Title: Under-The-Hill Saloon
Content: Under-the-Hill Saloon is one of the oldest buildings in the area, and its patrons of yesteryear were cut-throats, prostitutes and thieves. The area known as Natchez Under-the-Hill, was once a thriving port where cotton was loaded onto paddle-wheelers and shipped North to textile mills for processing. The saloon offers live music on weekends, and occasionally during the week as well. Grab a seat in the rocker on the front porch and catch a magnificent Mississippi River sunset during your visit.

Title: Area Lakes and Rivers
Content:
If you happen to be trailing a boat behind your vehicle as you travel, you may want to add a few extra days to your stay in Natchez because of the many beautiful lakes and waterways in the area. For pleasure boating with a little sight-seeing added in, Old River is a nature lovers paradise. Old River was once part of the Mississippi, and the main waterway still filters through it, giving boaters a sense of being on the mighty muddy without worrying about it's many hazards. Boating on the Mississippi River is certainly allowed, but we caution you to talk to locals about what to expect when you're out there.

Lake St. John and Lake Concordia offer great recreational Mississippi boating and have public boat ramps that charge a small launch fee. Other lakes in the area popular for water fun are Black River and Horseshoe lakes. For directions to these area lakes, grab a map at the Natchez Visitor Center on Canal St.

Title: St. Catherine Creek National Wildlife Refuge
Content:
St. Catherine Creek National Wildlife Refuge, encompassing 24,442 acres, with a potential size of 34,256 acres, is located in Adams County in southwest Mississippi. The headquarters lies ten miles south of Natchez. The western refuge boundary is formed by the Mississippi River. The eastern boundary meanders along the loessal bluffs and the southern boundary is the Homochitto River.
Habitat on the refuge offers a myriad of ecological niches for wildlife. Cypress swamps and hardwood forests vegetated with oak, gum, elm, ash, cottonwood and pine comprise thirty percent of the refuge. Ten percent of the acreage is open water, while the remaining property consists of cleared land and batture land.
The refuge is open to the public year-round. Available activities include fishing, hunting, bird watching and hiking. A three-mile nature trail is located near the headquarters where visitors can enjoy a peaceful opportunity to view wildlife.
Refuge headquarters are open 7:30 a.m. until 4 p.m. Monday - Friday. They are closed all Federal holidays. Refuge hours are sunup to sundown.

Title: Downtown Natchez Walking Tour
Content:
An excellent way to become familiar with Natchez is by touring the historic downtown area on foot. Most walking tours begin at Bluff Park, the grassy promenade that skirts Broadway and overlooks the river. 
Stop in at the Visitor Center, located at 640 South Canal Street, for a map with descriptions of the significant sites, and enjoy the wonderful architecture that makes downtown Natchez unique.

Title: Grand Village of the Natchez Indians
Content:
A religious structure once stood atop the Temple Mound and housed bones of previous chiefs (called Suns). A sacred perpetual fire was kept in the Temple's inner sanctum, symbolic of the sun, from which the royal family had descended.


The 128-acre Grand Village site features a museum, a reconstructed Natchez Indian House, and three ceremonial mounds. Two of the mounds, the Great Sun's Mound and the Temple Mound have been excavated and rebuilt to their original sizes and shapes. A third mound, called the Abandoned Mound, has been only partially excavated. After three major archaeological excavations at the Grand village by the Mississippi Department of Archives and History, no more digging investigations are planned for the site. The unexcavated areas of the site will be preserved intact, representing a sort of "time capsule" from the Natchez Indians' past. 


On the nature trail, native trees, flowers, and shrubs are identified. The Visitor Center offers interpretive exhibits and a gift shop featuring Native American crafts. A "Touch Table" invites children to handle tools and other objects the Indians employed.


Hours are Monday - Saturday 9:00 am until 5:00 pm, Sunday 1:30 pm until 5:00 pm.

Title: Natchez Manor
Content: The Manor has twelve beautifully appointed queen rooms, and two suite-sized king rooms overlooking Antiques Row. Downstairs is the 600 Franklin Piano Bar, which often provides live entertainment on the weekends and serves up a delectable line of libations. If you feel the need to take in some fresh air, visit the Rooftop Terrace Bar on the third floor to indulge in drinks and comfortable seating while jazz and blues fills the air.

Listing Amenity: Breakfast Included|Business Center|Coffee Maker|Credit Cards Accepted|Fitness Center|Hair Dryer|Handicap Access|Internet Access|Iron & Board|Meeting Space Available|Microwave|Off Street Parking|Outdoor Pool|Refrigerator|River Views
Title: Super 8
Content: Situated along the Bluff, the Best Western offers sixty rooms, with four handicapped units and twenty smoking units. There is one swimming pool and workout area. This Mississippi hotel does not allow pets. They offer a senior citizens discount and a group discount if you book ten or more rooms.

Title: Stanton Hall
Content:
Until recently, Stanton Hall was only available for rent to members of the Pilgrimage Garden Club, to use as a reception venue on their special day. Stanton Hall is now available to the public to rent as a reception and/or wedding venue. The interior of the home is absolutely stunning and features gorgeous Cornelius & Baker chandeliers in the main entry hall, dining room, library, and double parlors. The hallway runs the length of the house and is highlighted by ornate egg & dart molding which is anchored atop large dental molding, allowing for a molding depth of over ten inches. This venue is so extraordinary that your guests will talk about it for years to come.
The main house will accommodate quite a few folks, but if you need more space the Carriage House restaurant is located just across the courtyard from the main house, and it's a great place for a band and dancing. When the weather is nice, the courtyard can be used for outside bar and food table setups. Stanton Hall is also located within walking distance of some downtown hotels and bed & breakfast facilities.

Title: Delta Music Museum
Content:
Either on your way to visit Frogmore Plantation, or while enroute back to Natchez, there is a stop in Ferriday that you simply must make. The Delta Music Museum offers exhibits on sixteen rock and roll and blues musicians from the Mississippi River delta country. There is a "Walk of Fame" outside the building. The museum opened with a grant from the State of Louisiana but is operated by local volunteers. There is no admission charge; the facility relies on the sales of souvenirs. Visitors from all over the United States have signed the guestbook since the museum opened in the spring of 2002.
There are also exhibits on two well-known former Ferriday personalities not affiliated with the music industry: former CBS and ABC commentator Howard K. Smith (1914-2002) and Ann Boyar Warner (1908-1990), second wife of Warner Brothers studio mogul Jack Warner. There is a mural drawn in 1991 presented by Monterey High School in Concordia Parish. The first exhibit one encounters in the museum is a sculpture of the three Ferriday cousins at the piano: singers Mickey Gilley of Branson, Missouri, Jerry Lee Lewis and Jimmy Lee Swaggart, the latter an evangelist based in Baton Rouge. Other honorees are blues trombonist Leon "Pee Wee" Whittaker, a native of Newellton in northern Tensas Parish.

Title: Natchez in Historic Photographs
Content: Natchez is fortunate to have an outstanding collection of photographs depicting life in Natchez and on the riverfront from about 1845 to circa 1910. Family portraits, steamboats laden with enormous bales of cotton, and street scenes throughout the historic downtown area will keep you mesmerized for at least an hour when you tour the gallery. The gallery is located in the Stratton Chapel behind First Presbyterian Church on Pearl St. The exhibit is free, but donations are accepted to help offset the utility cost to display the exhibit. You simply have to add a trip to the chapel in your tour itinerary because the images you'll see truly reveal the history and majesty of Natchez.

Title: Soda Pops
Content: Soda Pops is located at the Natchez Mall on the outer strip, and their menu includes a great mix of ethnic dishes. Chicken Alfredo and Chicken Parmesan highlight the Italian side, Chicken Cordon Bleu adds a little French flair, and a great selection of Cajun dishes round it all out. The menu is extensive so you won't have a problem trying to satisfy any palate. It's a family restaurant with a fun atmosphere, reminiscent of family dining in the 60's. Be sure to come hungry because you won't leave that way. If somehow you are still hungry when you've finished your meal, try the Chocolate Lover's Sundae or a huge banana split. Soda Pops also makes its very own ice cream that will take you back to summer days on a family outing.

Title: White Turpin House
Content: Located within walking distance of downtown restaurants and shops, the White Turpin House is a charming bed and breakfast offering three bedrooms and two baths with 1 king and 2 queen beds. Breakfast consists of a voucher for Natchez Coffee Company located just around the corner. Bring a cup of joe back with you and enjoy reading a book in the White Turpin House library filled with Natchez and Mississippi history.

Title: Linden
Content: Why not include the accommodations and amenities of Linden in your wedding plans? We have plenty of guest rooms, so family and friends can be nearby to help you with the preparations and the celebration. Linden's dining room and parlors lend a delightful ambience as a reception or rehearsal dinner location. As you'll see in the photos, the gallery and courtyard give you plenty of room for the entire wedding entourage, as well as a great place for dancing, photos, and all the excitement that goes with your special day.

Title: Old South Winery
Content: It may seem a little unusual to be touting a winery as an attraction in the deep South, but it does exist and it is indeed something to experience. The winery is run by the Galbreath family and the wines are created from Muscadines (an American grape with a European name), grown in a vineyard right outside the facilities back door. After you take the 20 minute tour, the staff will pour you a small sample of each of the products they create from their grapes, so you can see what a treat they really are. The local favorite is a rose' labeled Miss Scarlet.

Title: Stanton Hall
Content: When you first get a glimpse of Stanton Hall, it will boggle your mind to know that builder, Dr. Frederick Stanton, paid a mere $83,000 to build this opulent, Greek Revival style mansion, which occupies an entire city block. Dr. Stanton was an Irish immigrant and he'd originally named the house Belfast, for obvious reasons. In addition to being a family physician, Stanton was a wealthy planter and cotton merchant. The house was built in 1857 and is noted for its scale, outstanding marble mantles, and large pier mirrors that give the double parlors infinite appeal. For a brief time, the house was home to Stanton College for young ladies and the name was then changed to Stanton Hall. Today the house is owned and maintained by the Pilgrimage Garden Club. You can learn more about Stanton Hall when you take the tour, or as you pass by in a horse-drawn carriage tour. Please visit the website link above to learn more about the home and how to purchase tour tickets.

Title: Natchez Trails
Content: The Natchez Trails are a combination of city streets and walkways dotted with interpretive panels depicting the history of the area in which you are walking. The trails run throughout the downtown area and along the bluff overlooking the river. Pedestrians and cyclists can share parts of the trails, and you can wind your way down to the edge of the mighty Mississippi River. Not only is it a great way to get some exercise, it is a great way to learn a lot about the abundant history of Natchez. The trail is wide enough atop the bluff to be shared by walkers and those just wanting to take a look at the river or watch a magnificent sunset over neighboring Louisiana. You can add an extra day to your stay just to spend it walking along the Natchez Trails.

Listing Amenity: Breakfast Included|Coffee Maker|Credit Cards Accepted|Free Parking Lot Available|Hair Dryer|Historic Property|Internet Access|Iron & Board|Long Term Stay Available|Meeting Space Available|Off Street Parking|Private Bath|Wireless Internet in Room
Title: Linden
Content: The Conner/ Feltus Family has owned Linden, one of the oldest antebellum homes in Natchez, for six generations-one of the few remaining long-term family owned bed and breakfasts in the area. It is said that the design of the front door was the inspiration for Tara in Gone With The Wind. The main part of the house was built in 1790, with the east wing addition in 1818 and the west wing addition in 1849. Linden is open for tour Thursday-Saturday 11am -2:00 p.m.

Title: Auburn
Content: Not only is Auburn a premier historic home and attraction for Natchez and a National Historic Landmark, Auburn is also a beautiful and convenient location for special events. Weddings, receptions, and bridal teas are held in this antebellum home. Call for availability and very reasonable rates.

Title: Dale's Catering
Content: Specializing in Southern Cuisine for events up to 500.

Title: Donut Shop, The
Content: Even if you are staying at a full service hotel or a bed and breakfast in Natchez, you somehow have to make your way to the Donut Shop. Now it may not sound like much, but when you sink your teeth into one of their sugary sensations, you'll know you've discovered something special. And if you don't manage to get by there early enough for donuts, you can indulge in an order of succulent tamales. They make their shucks from scratch and they are some kind of good. People have asked why we list them on our website, and we just think it would be crazy to not let everyone know about one of Natchez' best kept secrets.

Title: Slick Rick's Cafe
Content: Rick's Cafe is more than just a restaurant, and you'll find yourself walking away with some of the dry goods Rick offers for sale. Rick is a master spice mixer and you'll be treated to some of his mastery when you order practically any item on the menu. Nearly everything he serves up contains a taste of one of Rick's signature spices.

Title: Natchez Trails
Content:
Cyclists are welcome on the streets of downtown Natchez, and they may also join walkers in exploring the Historical Bluff Trail and parts of the Nature Trail overlooking the Mississippi River. These trails also provide interpretive wayside panels with interesting information and images. 

Many cyclists arrive in Natchez after journeying along the Natchez Trace Parkway, a 444-mile historic scenic byway from Natchez to Nashville, Tennessee.

Title: Magnolia Hall
Content: Construction on Magnolia Hall is believed to have begun in 1858, as the residence of Thomas Henderson, a Natchez native who became a wealthy cotton broker and merchant. The house was built on the site of the Henderson family home, Pleasant Hill, which was moved one block south to free the lot for the grander, more modern home. The name of the house was inspired by the plaster magnolia blossoms incorporated into the design of the parlor ceiling centerpieces. It was restored by the Natchez Garden Club as a house museum and is operated by the club today.

Title: William Johnson House, The
Content:
William Johnson was a free man of color in antebellum Natchez. He acquired several building in Natchez, approximately 2,000 acres of land south of town and he owned several slaves. He gained the respect of leading citizens of the time, some of whom he loaned money to, and local papers eulogized him after his untimely death.

William Johnson kept a diary for almost sixteen years, from 1835 until his death in 1851. It is the lengthiest and most detailed personal narrative authored by an African American during the antebellum era in the United States.

Johnson's diary evolved into an extraordinary record of social, economic, and political life in his hometown of Natchez, Mississippi, as seen through the eyes of a free man of color. Johnson covers everything from the mundane like Johnson's search for a lost cow to the momentous such as former president Andrew Jackson's visit to Natchez.

Operated by the National Park Service, William Johnson's House is open seven days a week from 9:00am-4:30 p.m. and is free to the public. It contains a bookstore, exhibit room and fully furnished recreated living quarters.

Title: William Johnson House, The
Content:
William Johnson was a free man of color in antebellum Natchez. He acquired several building in Natchez, approximately 2,000 acres of land south of town and he owned several slaves. He gained the respect of leading citizens of the time, some of whom he loaned money to, and local papers eulogized him after his untimely death.

William Johnson kept a diary for almost sixteen years, from 1835 until his death in 1851. It is the lengthiest and most detailed personal narrative authored by an African American during the antebellum era in the United States.

Johnson's diary evolved into an extraordinary record of social, economic, and political life in his hometown of Natchez, Mississippi, as seen through the eyes of a free man of color. Johnson covers everything from the mundane like Johnson's search for a lost cow to the momentous such as former president Andrew Jackson's visit to Natchez.

Operated by the National Park Service, William Johnson's House is open seven days a week from 9:00am-4:30 p.m. and is free to the public. It contains a bookstore, exhibit room and fully furnished recreated living quarters.

Title: Melrose
Content: One of 13 National Historic Landmarks in Natchez, Melrose is one of the best preserved and most significant historic sites in the entire South. The Greek Revival mansion was constructed circa 1845 for Pennsylvania native and Natchez attorney John T. McMurran. The home is operated by the Natchez National Park Service, United States Department of the Interior, and open daily for tour. Tickets may be purchased at The Natchez Visitor Center or at the home.

Title: Natchez Little Theatre
Content: Natchez Little Theatre offers numerous productions throughout the year and visitors are encouraged to spend one of their evenings in Natchez enjoying a local playhouse performance. The city is fortunate to have an array of surprisingly talented actors, and we are sure you will not be disappointed with your ticket purchase. Call the theatre for current productions or log onto their website for the season schedule.

Content: Located Under-the-Hill on the river front, Rivers Edge Guest Suites offer one the best views of the Mississippi River. These newly renovated suites are fully furnished and include a private bath and kitchen. Extended stay available.

Title: Monmouth Historic Inn
Content: Whether you are planning a prestigious conference or gala reception, our venue is truly inspiring. Gather attendees for a catered event in the Garden Room or a dinner to remember in the acclaimed 1818 Restaurant. Whatever the occasion, our seasoned experts, spectacular accommodations and attentive service promise an unforgettable event.

Title: Rhythm Night Club Museum
Content: The Rhythm Club Museum was constructed by the Sago Family in 2010, as a place to honor those wounded or killed in the tragic 1940 fire that took the lives of 207 Natchez citizens. There are testaments and images housed in the museum, and it's a "must see" attraction, which is worth giving to, an hour or more of your trip.

Title: Natchez State Park
Content:
Natchez State Park, located just a few miles North of Natchez, offers some of the best large and small-mouth bass fishing in the South. The State of Mississippi's record large-mouth bass was caught at the Natchez State Park, weighing a massive 18.15, pounds on December 31, 1992. The lake is well stocked with catfish, bream, and Florida largemouth bass. The park became a hot spot for bass fishermen when the Mississippi record large-mouth was caught in the lake. A Mississippi fishing license is required for all persons between the ages of 16 and 65. A launch is available for persons bringing their own boats.
Permit draw deer hunts start in October and end in January
Permit draw turkey hunts start in March and end in April

Title: Homochitto National Forest
Content:
You will find nature at its finest throughout the Homochitto National Forest. Spend hours hiking along the many creeks and trails that thread this enchanting woodland. The Clear Springs Recreational Area consists of a man-made lake, campground, picnic grounds, swim area, and two hiking trails. The longer of the two trails in the Recreation Area, Clear Springs Trail, is developing a reputation as one of the top three mountain-bike trails in Mississippi. Most campsites are secluded and either overlook the lake or are within an easy walk of the lake. Two CCC constructed pavilions on either side of the lake provide a comfortable place to enjoy the surrounding beauty and watch the wildlife. With a nice assortment of car, tent, recreational vehicle (RV), and motorhome-friendly camping, Clear Springs offers a diverse collection of activities that will keep all entertained, perfect for a family camping vacation.

For more information, or if you need to rent a bike, contact the Natchez Bike Shop at 601.442.4186.

Title: Natchez Trace Parkway
Content:
The Natchez Trace Parkway at Natchez is an area virtually littered with hiking trails, both marked and unmarked. If you are feeling a little adventurous and want to get a sense of what it was like for pioneers to experience difficult terrain and thick wooded areas, put on your hiking boots or a sturdy pair of sneakers and navigate your way along the Old Trace. 

The Trace is also a designated biking trail. It extends 444 miles from Natchez to Nashville, Tennessee. A federal parkway operated by the National Park Service, the Trace offers not only scenic beauty, but many historic markers to lead cyclists through some of the earliest history of the old Southwest Territory. If you're in Natchez, stop in at the Visitor Center and get a map, or contact info@visitnatchez.org to have one mailed to you. Cycling along The Natchez Trace is a great way to take in the raw beauty that lines both sides of this majestic trail. There are a few tough sloping hills to travel, so be sure you have plenty of gear range on your bike, and remember to take your camera along to capture some of nature's raw beauty along the Trace.

Title: Bluff Park
Content: The greatest natural attraction that Natchez has to offer is the Mississippi River, and the best vantage point from which to take in her beauty and splendor is the bluff. The best time to be on the bluff overlooking the river is at sunset, because, weather permitting, sunsets on the river can be a spectacular sight to behold.

Title: Moreton's Flowerland
Content: Moreton's is more than just a great place to get fresh cut flowers for your home, it is a magical gift shop with lots of unique treasures for your home or to give as gifts to newlyweds or graduates. It's a great place to just stop in and browse while you are antiquing as it is located on Franklin St. in the midst of Antique Row.

Title: Natchez Fine Framing & Art Gallery
Content: Natchez Fine Framing & Art Gallery is located in the heart of downtown and ready to complete the look of any artwork you need framed. They carry a wide selection of moulding and can precision cut your matte choice to finish your artwork with style. They also carry a great selection of works by local artisans, so if you prefer to get your hands on some original works and support a local artist, stop in and take a look at all that Natchez Fine Framing & Art Gallery has to offer.

Our commitment to excellence is evident in our seasoned staff, who boast over 70 years of hospitality experience. Whether you are looking for a one day event, or a weekend retreat, Dunleith is the ideal location - handling all of the details so you can focus on the business at hand.

Title: Hampton Inn & Suites
Content: If you're looking for a hotel with meeting space, the Hampton Inn of Natchez can host your group up to 40 with class-room style seating, or 60 theater style. The hotel has 82 rooms to accommodate your meeting attendees.

Title: Carriage House Restaurant
Content: The Carriage House Restaurant on the grounds of Stanton Hall, specializes in delicious Southern food, and is prepared with care by the hands and staff of Chef Bingo Starr of New Orleans. Chef Starr has taken great care to preserve the long standing favorite dishes of local patrons and brought a few new succulent entrees with his signature style to the menu like fried soft-shell crab. The Carriage House is owned and operated by the Pilgrimage Garden Club and is located on the Northwest corner of the grounds of historic Stanton Hall.

Title: Natchez Grand Hotel
Content:
Located across the street from the Natchez Convention Center, the Natchez Grand Hotel located in the heart of downtown Natchez. Opened in the Spring of 2008, the Grand was a welcomed addition to downtown lodging, offering 119 additional rooms to entice meeting and convention planners to Natchez.
19 of the rooms are suites and all are quite comfortable and elegantly appointed.

Title: Silver Spoon Catering
Content: Silver Spoon Catering service is owned and operated by master spice mixer, Rick Simon. Rick applies his culinary skills and spices to offer a great line of foods to cater meetings, luncheons, weddings or just about anything for which a group may gather. Give Rick a call to bring out the best for your guests at your next function.

Title: The House on Ellicott Hill
Content: The House on Ellicott Hill stands remarkably preserved on a perch where General Andrew Ellicott first raised the American Flag over Natchez on February 27th, 1797. The house has been well-maintained and is one of the earliest structures built in Natchez. It is open daily for tour and tickets may be purchased at the Natchez Visitor Center.

Title: Monmouth Historic Inn
Content:
Monmouth Historic Inn is one of the most monumental mansions in Natchez. The masculine strength of its design reflects both the forceful character of its most famous owner, General and subsequent Governor John A. Quitman, and the power of the Greek Revival style he chose for its ca. 1853 remodeling.
The home was built about 1818 for John Hankinson, an early Natchez postmaster who was a native of Monmouth County, New Jersey. Quitman, then a Natchez attorney, purchased the home in 1826. Daily 10 AM and 2 PM tour of the historic property may be purchased at the home.

Title: Darby's Gifts & Decorative Accessories
Content: Although Darby's is famous for it's freshly made fudge and many unique gifts, Darby carries a few clothing lines that are simply wicked cute. You can easily accessorize a cute top or sassy pair of jeans with a snazzy belt and then top if off with some one-of-a-kind jewelry pieces. Once you have your adorable ensemble in the bag, be sure to grab some fudge to snack on as you continue shopping in downtown Natchez.

Title: Arts Natchez Gallery
Content: Arts Natchez is appropriately named as it is the broker for a number of works by a variety of Natchez artists and craftsmen. The art gallery is situated in the heart of downtown Natchez on Main St. and if you spend a few minutes browsing through the local artwork, you'll know why each artist has a deep love for Natchez, and expresses it in their work. Be sure to add it to your Mississippi shopping itinerary.

Title: Towers, The
Content: The Towers is located on the north end of Natchez and rests on close to five beautifully landscaped acres. The Towers is one of Natchez' most opulent antebellum homes, surrounded by majestic oak trees planted long before the War Between the States. This wonderful Italianate home accommodates exceptional period pieces and unique collections rarely seen anywhere, including antique furniture, draperies, laces, beaded purses, Moser glass, chandeliers, bronze garden sculptures and more. National Register.
